Prolog
“I beg of you!” Queen Eirwen pleaded, “don't send her away! She's still a child!” The Ice King, accompanied by his royal advisor, looked down from his throne at his wife. She had given birth to a girl. At the thought of it, his expression darkened.
The girl resembled her mother greatly. She had pale blue eyes and white hair with blue strands. A girl meant weakness in the eyes of the Ice King. After all, he had only fathered sons up until that point.
“You have two options: Either you kill the child or you send it into the wilderness. That's its punishment for your failure, Eirwen.” He spat her name out as if it were poisonous. He always did that.
Frostfell was not always a single kingdom. Earlier, it consisted of two parts, the North and the South. In the North lay the non-magical kingdom, while in the South was a kingdom full of fantastic powers. But the North showed its greed and a never-ending war broke out between the two kingdoms, until the South finally offered a ceasefire.
The despair in the South was so great that the royal family was willing to do anything to end the bloodshed. They offered to send their only princess as queen to the North, where she would bear a son, the future king, and in this case, the North would unite with the South to form a kingdom. The North accepted the proposal, and Princess Eirwen married Prince Akull.
“I beg of you, my king, do with me as you please, imprison me, exile me, or kill me, but spare my child,” Queen Eirwen pleaded, holding her child in her arms.
The Ice King looked down at his queen with disgust. Perhaps, but only perhaps, would he show mercy to her. To the woman he had been married to for 22 years, who had stood by him in his darkest times and given him his sons.
“Alright. The child can stay in the palace,” he said, which was met with a sigh by the queen. “But,” he added, “you will be executed.”
The royal advisor and Queen Eirwen looked at each other in horror. Slowly, she turned her gaze to the ground. “Yes, my king.” She bowed her head.
The Ice King ordered the royal advisor to bring the queen's daughter to one of Eirwen's free rooms. Then he commanded the guards to take Eirwen to the execution site, where all the citizens of the city could watch.
As the guards escorted them to the execution site, a loud uprising broke out among the citizens, as they realized their beloved queen was to be executed. Some people were crying, others were screaming and attacking the guards. Others wondered why this was happening, but everyone was in agreement.
“Let her go!”
“Why are they doing this to her?”
As Eirwen approached the wooden stake, the most feared person in the kingdom appeared. The executioner. The woman who was still queen was to be burned alive. No one deserved such a death, not even a criminal. It was the most terrible thing that could happen to a person in Frostfell.
Eirwen was bound to the wooden stake, and the king declared in a speech how the queen had betrayed them all. The inhabitants of Frostfell refused to believe the king and did not want to accept his words. Then the executioner lit the wooden stake on fire, and a single tear rolled down the face of the former queen.
“Don’t give up, Kari.” This was the end of Queen Eirwen’s reign.
Deathly silence in the palace
Only a knock was heard from the room located on the left side of the eternally cold palace in the southern wing. The servants who passed by wondered what was inside the room. They were afraid of it. Rumors were circulating among the maids in the palace. It was said that the deceased wife of the Ice King, Eirwen, was in this room waiting to be released.
Her assumption couldn't have been more wrong, thought Ivory, and headed towards the southern wing, while the servants were bustling around and whispering to each other. They had no idea what was behind the door.
The rumors were of course also about Ivory, as Ivory was the only one allowed to enter the room.
Knock, knock. „Lady Kari, are you in there?“ Ivory whispered in front of the door adorned with snowflakes and a crown, the symbol of the royal family.
Ivory wondered if, unlike the last time, actual entry would be granted. I still have blue marks from the last time. Ivory chuckled at the thought. Kari had thrown a book against Ivory's shoulder, but apologized immediately when she realized who she had hit.
A single knock was heard from inside, likely to indicate that she was there. Where else could she be?
„May I enter?“ Ivory asked. Earlier, Ivory would have entered without asking.
Ivory heard a knocking sound from inside. That probably meant a "yes". The cold and the noise made Ivory shiver. It felt strange to hear a noise from a room that was supposed to be empty, although Ivory had been going there for several years.
"I'm coming in," Ivory said and slowly opened the door. The sight that greeted Ivory in the room was unusual for normal people, but not unexpected for Ivory. There was paper everywhere. Books were scattered all over the floor, the desk was broken, and several ice sculptures were lying around. There were no windows and little to no light. It was also colder than in the rest of the palace (which said a lot). The room looked like a snowstorm had passed through.
The girl was curled up in her bed, wrapped in her blanket, and reading one of her notebooks. A small lantern lit up the room.
"Which notebook is that?" Ivory asked and sat down beside Kari on the bed.
